summary:
# Meeting Summary: To review the financial results for Fiscal Year 2025 Fourth Quarter of Dell Technologies Inc.

## Key Points
- The meeting focused on reviewing the financial performance of Dell Technologies Inc. in the fourth quarter of FY '25.
- Key topics included services, Apple Intelligence, ISG, CSG, revenue growth, operating income, gross margin, innovation, servers, and storage.
- Discussions revolved around revenue growth, margin trends, competition, AI server market, and potential strategies for improvement.

## Discussed Topics
- The meeting began with an overview of Dell Technologies Inc. and its segments, followed by a detailed discussion on financial results for the fourth quarter.
- Performance metrics such as revenue growth, operating income, and key areas like ISG and CSG were highlighted.
- The differentiated value Dell brings to the marketplace, opportunities for margin improvement, and growth expectations in various segments were discussed.
- The growth and opportunities in storage, servers, and AI servers were explored, along with challenges faced in the HCI business.
- NVIDIA Corporation and Apple Inc. were discussed, focusing on their products, services, and strategic collaborations.
- Apple's revenue records, services revenue, gross margin, and product performance were analyzed, along with discussions on iPhone innovation and services growth.
- Insights on gross margin profiles, Services and Product gross margins, Apple Intelligence adoption, and potential tariff impacts were shared.

## Conclusions & Next Steps
- The meeting provided a clear understanding of Dell Technologies Inc.'s financial performance in the fourth quarter.
- Potential actions to be taken include leveraging storage business and IP to maintain margins, focusing on unique designs and value-add services for margin improvement, and driving efficiency and innovation through structural changes.
- Further analysis and decision-making may be required based on the discussions around revenue growth, margin trends, and competition in the AI server market.

division_metadata.summary: The beginning section of the transcript introduces Dell Technologies Inc. and its three segments: Infrastructure Solutions Group (ISG), Client Solutions Group (CSG), and VMware. The company provides a range of IT solutions and services worldwide. The call is then handed over to Paul Frantz, Head of Investor Relations, who provides an overview of the financial results for Fiscal Year 2025 Fourth Quarter.
division_metadata.next_steps: Review the earnings materials available on the IR website and the presentation for additional content. Guidance for the future will be covered on the call. A reconciliation of financial metrics to GAAP measures can be found in the web deck and press release. The company is well positioned for growth across all segments and is optimistic about the future in FY '26.

division_metadata.summary: The speaker discusses the company's performance in FY '25, highlighting revenue growth, operating income, and key areas like ISG and CSG. They also provide guidance for FY '26, mentioning expected revenue growth, EPS, and operational details. Questions from analysts focus on margin trends, competition, and ODM encroachment in the AI server market.
division_metadata.next_steps: The company plans to balance growth and profitability, manage pricing and competitive environment, and continue driving value for shareholders. They address concerns about ODM encroachment in the AI server market by highlighting their engineering and architecture capabilities, unique solutions for customers, and value-added services.

division_metadata.summary: Jeff Clarke discusses the differentiated value Dell brings to the marketplace with end-to-end solutions, focusing on large scale clusters and AI workloads. Yvonne McGill and Jeff Clarke express confidence in the demand for technology from the U.S. federal government. Aaron Rakers asks about margin profiles in AI business, and Jeff Clarke explains the opportunities for margin improvement through unique designs and value-add services. Michael Ng inquires about ISG margin outlook, and Jeff Clarke emphasizes leveraging storage business and IP to maintain margins. Ben Reitzes questions Dell's approach to tariffs, and Jeff Clarke highlights the company's agile supply chain and willingness to adjust prices. David Vogt asks about ISG xAI growth, and Yvonne McGill discusses expectations for growth across the full ISG portfolio.
division_metadata.next_steps: Monitor demand from U.S. federal government, focus on margin improvement through unique designs and value-add services, adjust prices accordingly to mitigate tariff impacts, continue leveraging storage business and IP to maintain margins, expect growth across the full ISG portfolio.

division_metadata.summary: The section discusses the growth and opportunities in storage, servers, and AI servers. Jeff Clarke explains the pivot to Dell IP storage and the challenges faced in the HCI business. The conversation also touches on traditional server growth, operating leverage, and structural changes being made to drive efficiency and innovation.
division_metadata.next_steps: Continue driving efficiency and innovation, focus on traditional server growth and attach store to GenAI servers.

division_metadata.summary: The section discusses NVIDIA Corporation and Apple Inc., providing an overview of their products, services, and strategic collaborations. It also includes a transcript section from an Apple earnings conference call with Tim Cook and Kevan Parekh.
division_metadata.next_steps: Further analysis of the financial performance and strategic direction of NVIDIA Corporation and Apple Inc. based on the information provided in the transcript section.

division_metadata.summary: Apple acknowledges the impact of wildfires in Los Angeles and expresses support for relief efforts. The company reports all-time revenue records in the December quarter, with revenue of $124.3 billion, up 4% year-over-year. They achieved records in various regions and markets, with significant growth in services revenue. Apple also highlights the success of Apple Intelligence features and their plans for international expansion. The section concludes with a focus on product revenue, services revenue, gross margin, operating expenses, net income, and diluted earnings per share.
division_metadata.next_steps: Provide more details for each revenue category.

division_metadata.summary: This section of the transcript discusses the revenue performance of various Apple products, including iPhone, Mac, iPad, Wearables, Services, and Enterprise. It highlights record revenue in several markets, customer satisfaction levels, and growth in active installed bases. Tim Cook also addresses questions related to Apple Intelligence impact on iPhone demand and challenges faced in the Chinese market.
division_metadata.next_steps: Provide an update on the capital return program in the next quarterly report. Monitor the impact of Apple Intelligence on iPhone demand. Keep an eye on the challenges and opportunities in the Chinese market.

division_metadata.summary: The section features discussions on iPhone innovation, record iPhone upgraders, iPad Pro sales, growth in emerging markets, gross margins, channel inventory, services growth, Mac and iPad sales, and supply chain planning in India.
division_metadata.next_steps: Further analysis and planning may be needed based on the discussions around iPhone innovation, record iPhone upgraders, growth in emerging markets, and supply chain planning in India.

division_metadata.summary: The section discusses the gross margin profile of the business, with Tim Cook and Kevan Parekh providing insights on Services and Product gross margins. Tim Cook highlights the success of Apple Intelligence and the outperformance of the 16 family over the 15 family. Kevan Parekh explains the factors driving Services gross margins and the favorable mix and leverage impacting Product gross margins. Richard Kramer asks about Apple Intelligence adoption and pricing strategies, with Tim Cook and Kevan Parekh providing responses. Atif Malik inquires about potential tariff impacts, and Ben Bollin asks about the average useful life of devices.
division_metadata.next_steps: A replay of the call will be available on Apple Podcasts or as a webcast on apple.com/investor. Press members can contact Josh Rosenstock, and financial analysts can contact Suhasini Chandramouli for additional questions.
